","Bishops Nympton, Devon, England":"Bishops Nympton, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","East Down, Devon, England":"East Down, Devon, England"},"en":{"about 1595–about 1625":"about 1595–about 1625","1595–1625":"1595–1625","1591–1655":"1591–1655","1619–1688":"1619–1688","1620–1655":"1620–1655","1622–Male":"1622–Deceased","1623–Female":"1623–Deceased","1555–Male":"1555–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1591":"1591","before 23 July 1622":"before 23 July 1622","about 1619":"about 1619","21 January 1618":"21 January 1618","1623":"1623","1622":"1622","1688":"1688","1655":"1655","1555":"1555","1620":"1620","about 1625":"about 1625","1595":"1595","1619":"1619","about 1595":"about 1595","1625":"1625","East Down, Barnstaple, Devonshire, England":"East Down, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Bishops Nympton, Devon, England":"Bishops Nympton, Devon, England, United Kingdom","East Down, Devon, England":"East Down, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rich","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname for a wealthy man (or perhaps in some cases an ironic nickname for a pauper), from Middle English, Old French <i>riche</i> ‘rich, wealthy’, a word of ancient Germanic origin, akin to ancient Germanic <i>rīc</i> ‘power(ful)’.","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Rich</i>, a pet form of any of the post-Conquest names beginning in <i>Rich-</i>, such as   Richer   and especially   Richard  . Compare   Rick  .","English: either a topographic name from Middle English <i>riche</i>(Old English <i>ric</i>) ‘stream’, signifying one who lived beside a stream, as at Glynde Reach (Sussex), or perhaps a habitational name from the (now lost) village of Riche (Lincolnshire)."],"variants":[{"name":"Ritchie","meanings":["Scottish: from a Scottish and northern English pet form of the personal name   Rich  , a short form of   Richard  . This surname is also common in Ulster.","Altered form of German   Richer   1."]},{"name":"Ritch","meanings":["English and Scottish (Orkney): either a variant of   Rich  , or perhaps from a short form of   Ritchie  , itself a diminutive based on <i>Rich</i>.","Altered form of German <b>Ritsch</b>, probably from a short form of an ancient Germanic personal name based on <i>rīc</i> ‘power(ful)’ or <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame, renown’; or an altered form of Swiss German <b>Rütsch</b>, <b>Ruetsch</b>, from Alemannic short forms of   Rudolf  ."]},{"name":"Riches","meanings":["English (Norfolk and Suffolk): variant of   Rich  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Richer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Normand, Armand, Fernand, Herve, Laurent, Marcel, Aurele, Donat, Elphege, Emile, Flore, Gilles.","English (East Anglia), French, and German: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>rīc</i> ‘power(ful)’ + <i>hari</i>, <i>heri</i> ‘army’. The name was introduced into England by the Normans in the form <i>Rich(i)er</i>, <i>Ricier</i>, but was largely absorbed by the much more common   Richard  .","Altered form of French <b>Héricher</b>: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Harigari</i>, composed of the elements <i>hari</i> ‘army’ and <i>gari</i> (from <i>garwa</i>) ‘ready, eager’ or <i>gari</i> ‘spear’, or a variant of <b>Hérissé</b>, a nickname for someone with spiky hair, from the adjective <i>hérissé</i>, a derivative of the verb <i>se hérisser</i> ‘to stand on end’."]},{"name":"Riche","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Ghislaine, Philippe, Yanick, Yvon.","English (London): variant of   Rich  .","French: nickname for a rich man or perhaps an ironical name for a pauper, from Old French <i>riche</i> ‘rich’. Compare   Leriche  ."]},{"name":"Richins","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Ricun</i>, a diminutive of   Rich  , itself a pet form of   Richard  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. It appears that a dialectally different (Norman or Picard) form of the French name, with medial /-k-/, also survived in England for a time alongside forms with original /-tʃ-/."]}]},{"name":"Anstice","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Anstis  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Anstis","meanings":["English: relationship name from a French-mediated form of the female personal name  <i>Anastasia</i>. The masculine form  <i>Anastasius</i> also existed and may have given rise to a patronymic. Both personal names are from adjectival forms of Greek  <i>anastasis</i> ‘resurrection’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Anstice Rich was born about 1595 as the daughter of Rich and ?. She married John Pyne on 21 January 1618, in East Down, Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. She died about 1625, at the age of 32."},"et":{"about 1595–about 1625":"umbes 1595–umbes 1625","1595–1625":"1595–1625","1591–1655":"1591–1655","1619–1688":"1619–1688","1620–1655":"1620–1655","1622–Male":"1622–Surnud","1623–Female":"1623–Surnud","1555–Male":"1555–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1591":"1591","before 23 July 1622":"enne 23. juulit 1622","about 1619":"umbes 1619","21 January 1618":"21. jaanuar 1618","1623":"1623","1622":"1622","1688":"1688","1655":"1655","1555":"1555","1620":"1620","about 1625":"umbes 1625","1595":"1595","1619":"1619","about 1595":"umbes 1595","1625":"1625","East Down, Barnstaple, Devonshire, England":"East Down, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bishops Nympton, Devon, England":"Bishops Nympton, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","East Down, Devon, England":"East Down, Devon, England"},"fi":{"about 1595–about 1625":"noin 1595–noin 1625","1595–1625":"1595–1625","1591–1655":"1591–1655","1619–1688":"1619–1688","1620–1655":"1620–1655","1622–Male":"1622–Kuollut","1623–Female":"1623–Kuollut","1555–Male":"1555–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1591":"1591","before 2